CTOR IDENTIFICATION\":\"Company A uses two materials in production, Material J and Material K. Material J is restricted to 12,000 kg, while Material K is restricted to 24,000 kg. The demand and material use for Products A, B, and C are shown in the table. Given the data, Material J is identified as the limiting factor.\"", "\"QUIZ: SALES RESTRICTIONS\":\"This quiz involves calculating the maximum contribution that can be achieved when Material R is restricted to 12,000 kg and sales of Product I are restricted to 4,000 units. The products H, I, and J have different contributions per unit and kg of R per unit. The quiz requires ranking the products and calculating the maximum contribution under sales restrictions.\"", "\"CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO (C/S RATIO)\":\"The contribution to sales ratio (C/S ratio) is calculated as the contribution per unit divided by the selling price per unit. It indicates the proportion of sales revenue that contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit.\"", "\"MAXIMUM CONTRIBUTION CALCULATION\":\"The maximum contribution is calculated by prioritizing products based on their contribution per limiting factor and producing them up to their maximum demand or until the limiting factor is exhausted.\"", "\"KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS\":\"Key Factor Analysis is a decision-making approach that prioritizes production based on the contribution per limiting factor, assuming a single objective of profit maximization and constant variable and fixed costs.\"", "\"LIMITATIONS OF KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS\":\"Limitations of Key Factor Analysis include assumptions of a single objective of profit maximization, constant variable and fixed costs, dealing with only one scarce resource, and applicability only to short-term capacity constraints.\"", "\"SHADOW PRICE\":\"Shadow Price\" refers to the additional contribution generated if one more unit of a scarce resource becomes available. It represents the maximum premium over the normal price that a company would be willing to pay for each additional unit. In the context of linear programming, the shadow price is the change in the optimal value of the objective function per unit increase in the right-hand side of a constraint. Essentially, it is the amount by which the objective function, such as contribution, will increase if an extra unit of a scarce resource is obtained at the standard price. For example, for the company Cut and Stitch, the shadow price for fabric is $10 per meter. The shadow price is a critical measure as it indicates the maximum amount a company should pay for one more unit of a scarce resource, such as timber, based on the contribution that the additional unit would generate.", "\"DECISIONS WITH A LIMITING FACTOR\":\"Decisions with a Limiting Factor involve determining which products to make in-house and which to outsource based on the savings per unit of scarce resource, prioritizing those with the greatest savings.\"", "\"MAKE OR BUY QUIZ\":\"The Make or Buy Quiz involves determining which components to make in-house and which to buy externally based on the savings per unit of scarce resource, given a limited supply of Material B.\"", "\"PRODUCT J\":\"Product J is a product with the third highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product H until the limiting factor is used up.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}